<section xml:id="sec-vectors-in-the-plane" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Vectors in the plane</title>

<definition xml:id="def-vector-plane">
	<title>(Vector in the plane)</title>
	
	
<statement>
<p>
A <term>vector</term> in the <m>(x, y)-</m>plane is a directed line segment, which is also called 
an `arrow'. The set of all vectors in the plane is denoted by <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<figure xml:id="fig-vector">
<caption>A vector in the plane</caption>
<image width="60%" xml:id="vector">
<latex-image >
\begin{tikzpicture}
<!--\tikzset{vector/.style={thick}}-->
	\draw (0, 0) node [anchor = north east] {$O$};
	\draw [vector,->] (-1, 0) -- (3,0) node [right] {$x$};
	\draw [vector,->] (0, -1) -- (0,3) node [above] {$y$};
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0, 0) -- (1.85, 2.60);
\end{tikzpicture}
</latex-image>
</image>
</figure>

<p>
An example is drawn in Figure <xref ref="fig-vector"/>. To understand the figure and the definition it is important to keep the following fact in mind: 
</p>
<assemblage xml:id="assemblage-mag-and-direction">
<p>Only the magnitude and direction of a vector matter, not its position in space.</p>
</assemblage>
<p>
In other words, we can think of a vector as an arrow `floating' in the plane, where translating the arrow (i.e.\ moving it without rotating or stretching it) gives a vector which is `the same' as the original vector. This is illustrated in Figure <xref ref="fig-vectranslates"/>: all of these arrows have the same magnitude and direction, so they represent the same vector.
</p>

<figure xml:id="fig-vectranslates">
<caption>These arrows all represent the same vector</caption>
<image width="60%">
<latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.5]
	<!--\tikzset{vector/.style={thick}}-->
	\draw (0, 0) node [anchor = north east] {$O$};
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (-0.65, 0) -- (1,0) node [right] {$x$};
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0, -0.65) -- (0,1) node [above] {$y$};
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0.1, 0.1) -- (0.4, 0.3);
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0.5, 0.1) -- (0.8, 0.3);
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0.1, 0.5) -- (0.4, 0.7);
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0.5, 0.5) -- (0.8, 0.7);
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (-0.4, 0.1) -- (-0.1, 0.3);
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (-0.4, 0.5) -- (-0.1, 0.7);
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0.1, -0.3) -- (0.4, -0.1);
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0.5, -0.3) -- (0.8, -0.1);
\end{tikzpicture}
</latex-image>
</image>
</figure>

<p>
We can also interpret vectors in an algebraic way, using coordinates. We will soon see that this is usually more convenient for doing calculations.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-notation-vectors">
	<title>(Vector terminology)</title>
	
	
<ul>
<li>
<p>If <m>A = (a_1, a_2)</m> is a point in the plane, then there is a vector from the origin <m>O = (0, 0)</m> to <m>A</m>. It is denoted by
<me>
\overrightarrow{OA} = \begin{bmatrix}a_1 \\ a_2\end{bmatrix}
</me>
or often by <m>[a_1, a_2]</m> to save space. Note that round brackets are used for points, while square brackets are 
used for vectors. We call <m>\overrightarrow{OA}</m> the <term>position vector</term> of the point <m>A</m>. 
The numbers <m>a_1</m> and <m>a_2</m> are called the <term>components</term> of <m>\overrightarrow{OA}</m>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="fig-position-vector">
<caption>The position vector <m>\overrightarrow{OA}</m> of a point <m>A = (a_1, a_2)</m></caption>
<image width="60%">
<latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale = 3]
	% Draw coordinates system
	\draw (0, 0) node [anchor = north east] {$O$};
	\draw [vector,->] (-0.4, 0) -- (1,0) node [right] {$x$};
	\draw [vector,->] (0, -0.4) -- (0,1) node [above] {$y$};
	
	% Add points and projections to axis
	\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0, 0) -- (0.7, 0.65) node [anchor = south west, xshift = -2mm] {$A = (a_1, a_2)$};
	\draw [dashed] (-0.08, 0.65) node [left] {$a_2$} -- (0.7, 0.65);
	\draw [dashed] (0.7, -0.08) node [below] {$a_1$} -- (0.7, 0.65);
	
	% Add vector
	\draw (0.35, 0.325) node [anchor = south east, xshift = 2mm] {$\overrightarrow{OA}$};	
\end{tikzpicture}
</latex-image>
</image>
</figure>
</li>

<li>
<p>
	More generally, if <m>A = (a_1, a_2)</m> and <m>B = (b_1, b_2)</m> are points, then we consider the vector 
	from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m>, written <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>. This is shown in <xref ref="fig-coordsAB"/>. 
	We say that <m>A</m> is the <term>tail</term> and that <m>B</m> is the <term>head</term> or <term>tip</term> of the 
	arrow. Since <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> is the displacement vector from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m>, we have
<me>
\overrightarrow{AB} = \begin{bmatrix} b_1 - a_1 \\ b_2 - a_2\end{bmatrix}
</me>.

<figure xml:id="fig-coordsAB">
<caption>A vector <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m></caption>
<image width="60%">
<latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=4.5]
	%x-y axis
\draw (0, 0) node [anchor = north east] {$O$};
\draw [vector,->] (-0.4, 0) -- (1,0) node [right] {$x$};
\draw [vector,->] (0, -0.4) -- (0,1) node [above] {$y$};

%vectors
\draw [vector,->,ultra thick] (0.75, 0.2) node [anchor = south west] {$A = (a_1, a_2)$} -- (0.2, 0.7) node [anchor = south west, xshift = -1mm] {$B = (b_1, b_2)$};

%components
\draw [dashed] (0.75, -0.08) node [below] {$a_1$} -- (0.75, 0.87); 
\draw [dashed] (0.2, -0.05) node [below] {$b_1$} -- (0.2, 0.87); 
\draw [dashed] (-0.08, 0.2) node [left] {$a_2$} -- (0.85, 0.2);
\draw [dashed] (-0.08, 0.7) node [left] {$b_2$} -- (0.85, 0.7);
\end{tikzpicture}
</latex-image>
</image>
</figure>
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
	When using a single-letter variable to refer to a vector, it will be typed in bold: for 
	example <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, <m>\mathbf{b}</m>, <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, or <m>\mathbf{v}</m>. In handwriting, 
	we instead use a squiggle under the vector, which looks 
	like <m>\underset{\sim}{a}</m>, <m>\underset{\sim}{b}</m>, etc.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>There is a special vector called the <term>zero vector</term>, written as <m>\mathbf{0}</m>. This is the 
	vector <m>\overrightarrow{OO}</m> from the origin to the origin with zero magnitude. Therefore
<me>
\mathbf{0} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\0 \end{bmatrix}
</me>.

<figure xml:id="fig-zero-vector">
<caption>The zero vector</caption>
<image width="60%">
<latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
	\draw (0, 0) node [circle, scale = 0.4, fill = black] {};
\draw (0, 0) node [anchor = north east] {$\mathbf{0}$};
\draw [vector,->] (-1, 0) -- (1,0) node [right] {$x$};
\draw [vector,->] (0, -1) -- (0,1) node [above] {$y$};
	
\end{tikzpicture}
</latex-image>
</image>
</figure>
</p>
</li>
</ul>
</definition>

<p>
Recall that different arrows can represent the same vector. Given any arrow, we can move it so that its tail is at the origin.</p>

<definition xml:id="def-standard-pos">
	<title>(Standard position)</title>
	
	
<statement>
<p>A vector with its tail at the origin is said to be in <term>standard position</term>.</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>All position vectors are in standard position, and all vectors in standard position are position vectors of their 
	tip. If <m>\mathbf{v} = \overrightarrow{OA}</m> is in standard position, where <m>A = (a_1, a_2)</m> is some point, 
	then <m>\mathbf{v} = [a_1, a_2]</m>. <em>So in standard position, the components of the vector 
		<m>\mathbf{v} = \overrightarrow{OA}</m> are exactly the same as the coordinates of the point <m>A</m></em>.</p>
<p>Let <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{CD}</m> be any two vectors in <m>\R^2</m>. Then the vectors are 
	equal if and only if they have the same displacement, i.e.<me>
\begin{bmatrix}
  b_1 - a_1 \\ b_2 - a_2
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
  d_1 - c_1 \\ d_2 - c_2
\end{bmatrix}
,
</me>
which is precisely when the vectors have equal components. So if <m>\mathbf{u} = [u_1, u_2]</m> 
and <m>\mathbf{v} = [v_1, v_2]</m>, then <m>\mathbf{u} = \mathbf{v}</m> if and only if <m>u_1 = v_1</m> and <m>u_2 = v_2</m>.</p>

<example xml:id="eg-finding-vectors">
<statement>
<p>Let <m>A = (-2, -1)</m>, <m>B = (1, 2)</m>, and <m>C = (3, 3)</m>. Which of the vectors <m>\overrightarrow{AB}, \overrightarrow{BC}</m>, <m>\overrightarrow{OC}</m> are equal?</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
	We calculate that <me>
\overrightarrow{AB} = \begin{bmatrix}1-(-2) \\ 2-(-1) \end{bmatrix}  = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 3\end{bmatrix},
</me>
and <m>\overrightarrow{BC} = [3-1, 3-2] = [2, 1]</m>, <m>\overrightarrow{OC} = [3, 3]</m>, and <m>\overrightarrow{OA} = [-2, -1]</m>. 
Thus <m>\overrightarrow{AB} = \overrightarrow{OC}</m>, and all the other vectors are distinct. 
(The components of <m>\overrightarrow{OA}</m> are the negative of the components of <m>\overrightarrow{BC}</m>, 
so <m>\overrightarrow{OA}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{BC}</m> have the same length, but they are not equal vectors 
because they point in opposite directions.)
</p>
</solution>
</example>


